# Fix macOS SIGKILL During Delta Upgrade

## Problem

Running `sentry cli upgrade` on macOS with the delta upgrade system causes
the process to be killed with SIGKILL. The shell reports `killed` with no
error message. On Linux, the same operation works fine.

## Root Cause

The delta upgrade system in `src/lib/bspatch.ts` uses `Bun.mmap(oldPath)`
at line 247 to memory-map the currently running binary (`process.execPath`)
for reading during patch application. `Bun.mmap()` defaults to
`{ shared: true }` which maps the file with `MAP_SHARED`.

On macOS, the kernel's **code signing enforcement** (`AMFI` — Apple Mobile
File Integrity) sends `SIGKILL` when a `MAP_SHARED` writable mapping is
created on a code-signed Mach-O binary. All Bun-compiled binaries have
ad-hoc code signatures. The `MAP_SHARED` mapping requests both `PROT_READ`
and `PROT_WRITE` from the kernel, which macOS rejects for signed executables
by killing the process.

On Linux, there is no such restriction — `mmap(MAP_SHARED, PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE)`
on a running ELF binary is perfectly legal.

### Call chain

```
upgrade.ts:614  → attemptDeltaUpgrade(version, process.execPath, destPath)
delta-upgrade.ts:614  → applyPatchChain(chain, oldBinaryPath, destPath)
bspatch.ts:247  → Bun.mmap(oldPath)  ← SIGKILL on macOS
```

## Fix

### Change 1: `src/lib/bspatch.ts` line 247

Replace:

```typescript
  // Memory-map old file: OS manages pages, 0 JS heap allocation
  const oldFile = Bun.mmap(oldPath);
```

With:

```typescript
  // Memory-map old file: OS manages pages, 0 JS heap allocation.
  // MAP_PRIVATE (shared: false) is required on macOS: the kernel's code
  // signing enforcement sends SIGKILL when a MAP_SHARED writable mapping
  // is created on a code-signed Mach-O binary (which the running CLI is).
  // MAP_PRIVATE is safe because we only read the data — any copy-on-write
  // pages are never materialized.
  const oldFile = Bun.mmap(oldPath, { shared: false });
```

**Why `{ shared: false }` works:**
- `shared: false` → `MAP_PRIVATE` (copy-on-write mapping)
- macOS allows `MAP_PRIVATE` on code-signed binaries because writes go to
  private pages, not back to the file — the code signature is never violated
- We only read from `oldFile` (never write), so no COW pages are ever
  allocated — memory behavior is identical to the current code
- Performance is unchanged: read-only access patterns on `MAP_PRIVATE` are
  equivalent to `MAP_SHARED` reads

### Why not other approaches

| Alternative | Reason rejected |
|-------------|----------------|
| `Bun.file(oldPath).arrayBuffer()` | Reads entire ~100 MB binary into JS heap. Works but wasteful. |
| Copy binary to temp, mmap the copy | Extra I/O + disk space for no benefit — the copy has the same code signature |
| Platform check (`process.platform === "darwin"`) | Unnecessary — `MAP_PRIVATE` is correct on all platforms for read-only access |
| Skip delta on macOS | Defeats the purpose of the delta upgrade system |

## Testing

The existing `test/lib/bspatch.test.ts` and `test/lib/bspatch.property.test.ts`
tests should continue to pass since the fix only changes the mmap flags, not
the patching logic. The test fixtures are plain binary files (not Mach-O
signed binaries), so the tests wouldn't have caught this issue — and they
still won't reproduce it on Linux CI. This is an OS-level kernel behavior
that can only be verified manually on macOS.

No new tests are needed. The fix is a one-line change with well-understood
semantics.

## Verification

After the fix, test on macOS:
```bash
sentry cli upgrade
```
Should complete without SIGKILL, either applying a delta patch or falling
back to full download.
